> Flavourful lamb mince mixed with sweet, tender root vegetables, topped with silky, smooth mashed potatoes and baked until golden and bubbling, the classic shepherd's pie will never disappoint. We've added the fragrant kick of Indian spice for a stand-out dish.

Bring a #large saucepan{} of water to the boil with a pinch of @salt{} for the potatoes. Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 3cm chunks (no need to peel!). When boiling add the potatoes and cook until you can easily slip a knife through, ~{15-20%mins}.

Meanwhile, heat a splash of @oil{} in a #large frying pan{} on a high heat. When hot, add the @lamb mince{200%g}. Cook until browned, ~{4-5%mins}, breaking it up with a #wooden spoon{} as it cooks. Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(finely chopped). Trim the @carrot{1}, then quarter lengthways (no need to peel). Chop widthways into small pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the @red chilli{1} lengthways, deseed then finely chop.

Once browned, tip the mince into a #small bowl{} and drain off any excess fat. Lower the heat to medium and add the chopped onion and carrot to the now empty #frying pan{}. Cook until softened and turning brown, ~{6-7%mins}. Add the @ground turmeric{2%tsp}, half the garlic and half the red chilli, cook for ~{2%mins}, stirring regularly. Return the lamb mince to the frying pan with the @chopped tomatoes{1}(finely chopped), a splash of @water{} and season well with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Simmer until thick and tomatoey, ~{8-10%mins}.

Once the potatoes are cooked, drain them in a #colander{}. Return the potato to the #saucepan{}, add a knob of @butter{knob} and a splash of @milk{a splash} (if you have some), mash until smooth with a #potato masher{}. Season to taste with salt and pepper and stir through the turmeric. Cover with a #lid{} to keep warm.

Preheat your #grill{} to the highest setting. Transfer the lamb mixture to a #baking dish{}, (quickly wash out your frying pan to use later on.) Top the lamb with dollops of mashed potato. Spread it out evenly over the filling using the back of a #spoon{}. Use the back of a #fork{} to make ridges in the potato. Pop under the grill until browned, ~{3-5%mins}.

While the pie is under the grill, heat your frying pan over a medium heat with a knob of @butter{knob} (if you have some) or a drizzle of @oil{}. Once hot, add the remaining garlic and chilli (add as much as you like). Add the @shredded savoy cabbage{100%g} and stir-fry for ~{1%minute} then add a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{} and a splash of @water{}, cover with a lid or #tin foil{} and cook until just tender, ~{2-3%mins}. Serve alongside the shepherds pie. Enjoy!